as last year according to deloitte’s  annual holiday survey the expected uptick which is occurring despite flat income growth is attributed by deloitte economists to an improving labor market increasing home values and lower gas prices the survey also found that concerns about personal data protection persist nevertheless over half of those surveyed indicate they will continue to patronize retailers that have experienced a data breach views  analysis four ways cfos can avoid a digital talent crunch technology is redefining how work gets done both in the back office and in frontline operations while the rapid growth of digital technologies creates new opportunities for finance it also creates the potential for a digital divide if members of the finance team lack the necessary skillsets and business acumen they may not be able to make the most of these new digital capabilities learn how cfos can help their organization advance its digital efforts by focusing on leadership culture skills development and engagement keeping finance talent relevant to changing needs charles holley cfoinresidence it’s no secret that talent is key to a cfo’s success yet talent is a perennial top challenge for cfos that’s partly due to the continually changing definition of what it means to have a talented finance team says charles holley an independent senior advisor to deloitte drawing on his extensive leadership experiences he explains how to identify recruit and develop the people best suited for the fastchanging demands of finance the key he says is finding the best athletes and keeping their capabilities relevant and aligned to the needs of the business fpa why talent counts and what cfos can do to improve it to elevate the strategic contribution that a finance organization’s fpa team can make cfos should focus on developing the team’s technical professional and leadership competencies specifically they can use a fourpart model that provides opportunities to gain education and experience with exposure to key decisionmakers and the expectation that fpa will function more strategically rotating talent from fpa into the business and back again can also help team members acquire both a broader understanding of the organization and the specialized knowledge that can make this function integral to the organization’s success editors choice leading business transformation at the speed of tech kelly kramer cisco cfo leading a major business transformation from the cfo seat takes strategic vision a close partnership with the ceo and business leaders and a finance team with a changeagent mentality according to kelly kramer cfo of cisco systems inc she talks about her role leading cisco’s business transformation and driving innovation and growth through finance with kirsten rhodes managing director deloitte services lp ms kramer also discusses how she’s developing finance talent and the importance of a strong financeit relationship new market dynamics bring change to cfo searches the disruption characterizing the business climate appears to be spilling into the cfo job market impacting what companies seek in their next cfo and how they conduct their searches according to jenna fisher who leads the global corporate officers sector at executive search firm russell reynolds associates she discusses a host of recent trends she is seeing in cfo searches including rising interest in “best athlete” candidates and those with global and strategysetting experience a decrease in internal cfo promotions and an increase in confidential searches china spotlight how cfos can monitor and mitigate directional shifts in china’s currency—an update changing dynamics in china’s currency policy and market volatility continue to add to uncertainty on the direction of the renminbi rmb something cfos of multinational companies operating in china should consider monitoring more closely george warnock americas leader of the deloitte chinese services group and ken dewoskin independent senior advisor to the group discuss how china’s equity market turbulence could impact the rmb and steps cfos can take to monitor the currency’s direction and help mitigate the effect of a significant shift about deloitte insights deloitte’s insights for cfos provides financial executives a customized resource to help them address the strategic operational and regulatory issues they face in managing their finance organizations and careers with topline digests research perspectives and technical analyses mark buthman facilitating and framing issues  thinkleaders united states search within thinkleaders thinkleaders new thinking pacesetters events frank discussions at cannes lions finance mark buthman facilitating and framing issues june    written by think leaders categorized finance  pacesetters share this post mark buthmanchief financial officer kimberlyclark corporation kimberlyclark has a great tradition of innovation it pioneered five of the eight consumer product categories where it does business including facial tissues training and youth pants and bathroom tissue now the company is under pressure to innovate in the way it does business too as it drives an ambitious international expansion mark buthman who has been chief financial officer for more than  years sees the cfo as a facilitator and framer of issues someone who can help the company expand rapidly even while improving its profitability here he explains how the role of cfo at kimberlyclark is changing what are the primary opportunities and challenges that face kimberlyclark the biggest driver of our business is international growth as per capita incomes grow around the world our categories are among the first that consumers enter for the first time or where they aspire to better performance better brands at the same time as the economy has become more difficult in developed markets we need to provide differentiation and clear value in terms of the performance and the perception of our products people are nervous about spending our products have to be demonstrably better than the alternatives so we have to have great product innovation and great product performance and we have to communicate that performance effectively all over the world in the emerging markets are you designing new business models and changing pricing to grow rapidly the key for us is balancing the global approach—scalable ideas and model—with the local market and local consumer keeping that balance is a challenge because you want to drive scale but in local markets there are different demand dynamics that you have to respond to for instance in china with disposable diapers there are clear expectations in terms of fit and leakage protection and yet they don’t want to change their babies as often as folks in the united states do with huggies we have to figure out how to deliver to those expectations at a price point the parents in china can afford we’ve had to find a way to manufacture and to provide the same functional benefit at a lower cost how did the cfo function play a role in that we partnered with the businesses to design a new product development procurement manufacturing and marketing model in china first we framed the problem that needed to be solved then we used information and analytics to provide some options what about in the developed markets what role are you playing there in every one of our categories we have to be competitive on price and have the best performing product that’s a universal truth in a big box store where you have our products side by side with another premium product we have to price very competitively or the consumer may switch so the role we play is in working with all the parts of our company—supply chain product development manufacturing— to create a cost structure that will support sustainable investment and make the product successful we bring the various stakeholders together we’re at the table when every key strategic decision is made we bring an independent economic perspective to the decision you have been cfo for more than  years how is the role changing some things are the same we don’t have unlimited resources so the cfo has to be the champion of resource allocation next we help with setting goals and targets that balance investments we take into consideration the degree of difficulty in getting something done risks and prospects for growth profitability and returns on capital then we hold teams accountable for their business results what’s changing though is the role of information technology in business earlier the cfo had access to all the information aggregated it and used it when making decisions now thanks to the internet and other technologies people throughout the organization have great access to information in the old days my job was directing and deciding now i should be facilitating orchestrating and influencing rather than mandating my expectation for my team and myself is that we develop a compelling business case and champion the change this way we’re working to drive change that is embraced we’re not so much pushing as the organization is pulling how do you help drive agility within the business the competitive environment has accelerated so much that we’ve got to be much more nimble much more agile much more wired in in the planning process there are much shorter lead times to project what the business is going to do at kimberlyclark we talk a lot about taking smart risks in a lot of companies the finance role is being a policeman but here we’re more of a teacher a leader a facilitator if our role is just to say no any time there’s a risk on the table we’ re not going to create much value for our shareholders our job is to help frame issues and get the organization to take smart calculated risks will you provide an example where you played the facilitator and framer role in an effort that let to a new revenue opportunity one area where we have done that is in the international expansion we have helped the company size up the emerging markets opportunities and figure out how to successfully compete in them now about half of our total capital spend is on building capacity and innovation in  for the first time we spent more capital in developing markets than in developed markets the shift in our capital allocation didn’t mirror the growth of business in these newer markets it led the transformation of the business that was a shift that my team led at the same time we have dramatically increased marketing in developing markets—to establish our brands there we have done that while increasing our gross margins that’s possible because of the cost improvements we’re making what is technology’s role in making the company more efficient innovative and competitive the internet and transparency of consumer information and competitive cost information is changing the way the whole world works your ability to sustain a pricing advantage in an internetdriven world is about a nanosecond so we’re joined at the hip with the cio jennifer sepull in fact she reports to me our goal is to provide information so business leaders can make better faster and higher quality decisions my vision for our organization is to have the right information on the desktop for all of our decision makers so they can make a quality decision when they need to make it we’re not there yet the cio and the cfo can partner to bring that reality to life we need mobile and collaboration technologies to drive team engagement across functional and geographic boundaries if i can use technology to get information more rapidly across our organization it gives us the opportunity to unlock the best ideas technology also improves our ability to do things better we can compare our performance against benchmarks and we can share our problemsolving experiences i don’t have to wrestle with an issue by myself i can find somebody else who has dealt with the same issue already and learn from him or her the connections that technology provides are invaluable how has your relationship with the it function changed over the years in the old days the cfo was the gatekeeper of the money the cio had to come and ask for money like everybody else now it’s more a conversation about how we invest in it as a core capability we’re helping control costs by adopting standard technologies and standard ways of handling data across the organization and by eliminating redundant systems once you’ve done that you can free up resources to spend on new capabilities on innovation so the most important role for the cfo is framing issues that create new opportunities enthusiasm and energy throughout the company related reading new thinking hone your powers of persuasion finance is leading transformation and growth it’s time to put mobile first the consumability of data is as important as the data itself be global and local think leaders analytics cfo cio consumer products finance pacesetter previous post fernando a gonzález making a more flexible and efficient organization next post gary crowe becoming more agile in a fastchanging environment follow the conversation tweets by ibmthinkleaders save save save save rss feeddigital founders panel ox verte odysia  an ideas companyfrankly the internet of things is the next step in addressabilityfrankly your brand is only as good as your customer experiencefrankly talking like a millennial isn’t enough – with ibm ix  micfrankly you should be thinking about blockchain as the next big thing in programmaticerrol baran svp business development and innovation bbcronalee zaratebayani head of integrated marketing  digital advancement the hershey companygabriel fernandes head of consumer experience pernod ricardhas human communication become botifeddesigning like you’re there what i learned using vr for architecture more pacesetters stories pacesetters digital founders panel ox verte odysia  an ideas company ibm’s robert schwartz talks about entrepreneurship the importa