w sits on the boards of forprofit and nonprofit organizations and serves on the financial executives advisory group for deloitte’s cfo program mr buthman discusses what his year term as cfo taught him the steps he took to develop finance employees to their full potential and how he helps to guide current and aspiring cfos in this conversation with sanford sandy cockrell iii us national managing partner cfo program deloitte llp mr buthman also talks about the relationship between the board and the cfo and what boards expect of cfos sanford cockrell iii sandy cockrell you spent your entire career at kimberlyclark but not always in finance what were the key milestones in reaching the cfo position mark buthman i always wanted to drive business results to lead teams and to coach influence and develop people those were more important motivators for me than becoming cfo in fact i think the nonfinance roles i took on were the most important because they forced me to lead without relying on my financial skills and experiences running a tissue plant for example was a fantastic leadership opportunity because i literally brought nothing to the table other than perhaps the ability to do the budget everything else was about getting the team to where it needed to go at one point i was also asked to support some ma transactions but i didn’t have extensive training in it at the time those projects came with a lot of responsibility and forced me to learn skills and a new nomenclature very rapidly they really tested my learning agility and i’m grateful that i had the opportunity to stretch myself in a new space sandy cockrell you believe in the value of measuring and improving employee engagement how have you seen such efforts translate into results mark buthman i think a highly engaged workforce correlates to improved bottomline performance about halfway into my tenure as cfo we did an engagement survey that showed that some people in my finance organization didn’t feel like they were empowered to take risks they felt like they were more encouraged to cut costs and avoid risks than to drive growth in the business that frustrated me because business is about taking calculated risks and to me the finance organization is the ideal resource to be able to help the business determine riskreward tradeoffs i shared my concern with the head of risk management at the time and he worked with someone from our legal team to put together a program called “smart risktaking” within about  months the program trained  people both within and outside finance “smart risktaking” ultimately became an element of one of the core behaviors we expected from anyone in a leadership role sandy cockrell you also have advocated for pushing decisionmaking down in the organization what is the benefit of doing that mark buthman the role of a finance leader is to drive business performance and much of that depends on empowering the organization to make smart decisions strategically tactically and operationally there are times when you have to take the decision or draw a bright line that can’t be crossed but i think leaders are most effective when they take on the roles of coach teacher and influencer so their teams make the calls and own the results prior to the digital revolution the role of the cfo was to accumulate information from different silos bring it together and make decisions at the top of the organization there was really no other way to do it today most of the information needed to make decisions—even big strategic decisions—is readily available to many people in the organization which gives the cfo a golden opportunity to push decisionmaking down and empower teams to do that one has to be good at articulating a clear vision and giving people a framework one colleague described it as “the freedom of boundaries” meaning that he understood his latitude to make decisions as long as he knew what lines couldn’t be crossed as the cfo when you empower teams this way it can free you up to have much greater influence on the business  if every decision needs to come to your desk that’s going to slow decision making and limit your impact sandy cockrell you have significant experience as a board director what has it taught you about the relationship between the board and the cfo mark buthman serving on boards has exposed me to a diverse range of business strategies and leadership styles and has given me an appreciation for the importance of looking at a business from the outside in as a cfo my experience as a board member helped me understand how to communicate to the board the essential things they need to know while keeping the discussions at a high level until i sat on the other side of those conversations as a director i didn’t fully realize the importance of communications from a board member’s perspective i stress to sitting cfos that working with the audit committee in particular can provide them with an opportunity to highlight talent in the finance organization that helps foster more trust within the audit committee that the right people are in the right roles and they are going to do the right thing board members can actually help cfos develop their talent because they bring an objective perspective free of the daytoday relationships with people i’ve also learned that what boards want to see most in a cfo is someone with a strong functional and ethical foundation a strategic mindset and the ability to attract and build exceptional talent with strong communication and influencing skills and of course cfos need to understand when and how to alert the board to an emerging issue having served in both roles i encourage cfos to view the board as a resource and to make the effort to reach out to an individual board member if their skills can help address a particular issue including talent matters sandy cockrell you spend some of your time coaching other cfos what do you encourage them to focus on mark buthman i tell new cfos that they now have broader responsibilities than they’ve ever had before yet they have only half the time to meet them all that’s because more of their time is committed to board meetings investor calls and roadshows earnings forecast reviews ceo leadership meetings travel and other activities their calendar may be booked a full year out or more so as cfo the ability to manage your time effectively and to invest it where it makes the most difference is something you have to get your arms around one technique that helped me—even although it goes against conventional teaching—was to drop most of my oneonone meetings we made exceptions for cases where someone needed coaching help in setting direction or problemsolving or needed to communicate an emerging issue i also encourage the cfos i work with to help their teams identify and act on their purpose and values as much or more than the work they do  for example when i became cfo i had a game plan to improve our core finance capabilities set a clear tone at the top have a robust set of internal controls and address talent development typical expectations for many finance organizations i refer to those as the “what” despite all the work being done however i had the sense that our finance organization including myself was still not reaching its full potential eventually i realized it was because we had not addressed the “why”  so together we rallied around a very simple message to empower our leaders to think like a cfo with a mission to drive business results inspire our teams and each other and transform the way we did our work  if everyone in an organization feels empowered to focus on those three things good outcomes can happen  at the end of the day if an organization is  right and  aligned that is a terrific result and much better than being  right and only  aligned editor’s note this article is part of an ongoing series of interviews with ceos cfos and other executives mr buthman’s participation in this article is solely for educational purposes based on his knowledge of the subject and the views expressed by him are solely his own this article should not be deemed or construed to be for soliciting business for any of the organizations mr buthman has represented in his career nor does deloitte advocate or endorse their services or products read more about talent management january    am questions write to deloittecfoeditor follow us on twitter deloittecfo this publication contains general information only and deloitte llp and its subsidiaries deloitte are not by means of this publication rendering accounting business financial investment legal tax or other professional advice or services this publication is not a substitute for such professional advice or services nor should it be used as a basis for any decision or action that may affect your business before making any decision or taking any action that may affect your business you should consult a qualified professional advisor deloitte shall not be responsible for any loss sustained by any person who relies on this publication copyright   deloitte development llc previous creating value with outsource assurance reporting next want to make fpa a business partner start by building capacity text size regular medium large google print search cfo journal market data stocks  pm et  djia   sp    ftse   nikkei    rates  pm et  us  yr   ger  yr   spn  yr   jpn  yr   futures  pm et  oil   gold   silver   copper   fx  pm et  euro    yen    pound    swiss frank    related deloitte insights digital finance why and how robots are joining the team as finance becomes more digital one technology receiving both attention and investment is robotic process automation rpa is a relatively simple and inexpensive softwarebased technology that replicates keyboard and mouse actions commonly performed by knowledge workers it can handle repetitive rulesbased tasks and is now being combined with cognitive capabilities to further increase its value learn how the technology works and how to create pilot programs that can be scaled to address many finance needs red yellow green building a strong team during a transition firsttime or newly hired cfos need to make critical decisions early on about who to place in top positions or risk being saddled with an underperforming team that can hamper the cfo’s ability to meet their strategic goals dr ajit kambil global research director for deloitte’s cfo program and creator of its executive transition lab explains why so much depends on the talent decisions cfos make in their first  days and describes techniques for effectively evaluating and developing finance staffers assessing risk in incentive compensation plans incentive compensation plans can align employee behaviors with a company’s objectives but there have been examples of such programs resulting in unintended consequences that have damaged reputations and financially harmed companies and shareholders learn why finance leaders should consider whether there is a process in place to identify and mitigate several potential risks of incentive compensation plans including financial reputational operational and employeeretention risks views  analysis four ways cfos can avoid a digital talent crunch technology is redefining how work gets done both in the back office and in frontline operations while the rapid growth of digital technologies creates new opportunities for finance it also creates the potential for a digital divide if members of the finance team lack the necessary skillsets and business acumen they may not be able to make the most of these new digital capabilities learn how cfos can help their organization advance its digital efforts by focusing on leadership culture skills development and engagement keeping finance talent relevant to changing needs charles holley cfoinresidence it’s no secret that talent is key to a cfo’s success yet talent is a perennial top challenge for cfos that’s partly due to the continually changing definition of what it means to have a talented finance team says charles holley an independent senior advisor to deloitte drawing on his extensive leadership experiences he explains how to identify recruit and develop the people best suited for the fastchanging demands of finance the key he says is finding the best athletes and keeping their capabilities relevant and aligned to the needs of the business fpa why talent counts and what cfos can do to improve it to elevate the strategic contribution that a finance organization’s fpa team can make cfos should focus on developing the team’s technical professional and leadership competencies specifically they can use a fourpart model that provides opportunities to gain education and experience with exposure to key decisionmakers and the expectation that fpa will function more strategically rotating talent from fpa into the business and back again can also help team members acquire both a broader understanding of the organization and the specialized knowledge that can make this function integral to the organization’s success editors choice leading business transformation at the speed of tech kelly kramer cisco cfo leading a major business transformation from the cfo seat takes strategic vision a close partnership with the ceo and business leaders and a finance team with a changeagent mentality according to kelly kramer cfo of cisco systems inc she talks about her role leading cisco’s business transformation and driving innovation and growth through finance with kirsten rhodes managing director deloitte services lp ms kramer also discusses how she’s developing finance talent and the importance of a strong financeit relationship new market dynamics bring change to cfo searches the disruption characterizing the business climate appears to be spilling into the cfo job market impacting what companies seek in their next cfo and how they conduct their searches according to jenna fisher who leads the global corporate officers sector at executive search firm russell reynolds associates she discusses a host of recent trends she is seeing in cfo searches including rising interest in “best athlete” candidates and those with global and strategysetting experience a decrease in internal cfo promotions and an increase in confidential searches china spotlight how cfos can monitor and mitigate directional shifts in china’s currency—an update changing dynamics in china’s currency policy and market volatility continue to add to uncertainty on the direction of the renminbi rmb something cfos of multinational companies operating in china should consider monitoring more closely george warnock americas leader of the deloitte chinese services group and ken dewoskin independent senior advisor to the group discuss how china’s equity market turbulence could impact the rmb and steps cfos can take to monitor the currency’s direction and help mitigate the effect of a significant shift about deloitte insights deloitte’s insights for cfos provides financial executives a customized resource to help them address the strategic operational and regulatory issues they face in managing their finance organizations and careers with topline digests research perspectives and technical analyses kimberlyclark cfo mark buthman announces plans to retire at year end kimberlyclark cfo mark buthman announces plans to retire at year end company names maria henry former hillshire brands cfo as successor feb    et from kimberlyclark corporation     facebook twitter pinterest dallas feb   prnewswire  kimberlyclark corporation nyse kmb today announced that chief financial officer mark buthman  has announced his intention to retire at the end of  the company has named maria henry  as buthmans successor henry who was the cfo of hillshire brands company from  to  and cfo of sara lees north american retail and food service business from  to  will become senior vice president and chief financial officer effective april  and will work with